Add support for making Tornado dump its stack via SIGUSR1/2.

With this change,

pkill -SIGUSR1 -f runtornado

will dump the stack and SIGUSR2 will enable an interactive debugging
session.

This fixes #613 for Tornado which was the original motive for that
ticket; I'm not sure whether we want to do this for our Django
processes as well, but it would be easy to do so if we did.

Moves each GTFS class to its own file.

_transitfeed.py was deleted, and its contents splitted into several files - one per GTFS class, plus the problem-reporting and utility classes and methods.

Users of the transitfeed library should *not* have to modify their programs.

Addresses issue 196

Review at http://codereview.appspot.com/216055

Introduction of an object factory for standardizing loading of GTFS files in the
transitfeed package.

For this two new classes were introduced, HeadwayPeriod and GtfsFactory.

Not all files were moved to this standardized loading. calendar.txt,
calendar_dates.txt, shapes.txt and stop_times.txt are still loaded in the same
way.

The performance penalty, after several profiling runs with various feeds on my
machine, is about ~3%. In some feeds a bit more (5% at most) and in others a bit
less (%1).

Changes in behavior on the transitfeed package:

 * Invalid values in routes.txt's route_color and route_text_color are now replaced by the respective default values
 * Schedule.AddAgencyObject no longer calls Validate() by default on the Agency object being added
 * Schedule.AddTripObject no longer calls Validate() by default on the Trip object being added
 * Schedule.AddRouteObject no longer calls Validate() on the Route object being added
 * Instanciation of GTFS classes should not be done directly, but through GtfsFactory instead

Changes to the transitfeed package:

* Loader and Schedule classes are now retrieved from the GtfsFactory instead of being instantiated directly.

This revision contains the first extension of the FeedValidator.

It contains the general 'skeleton' for extensions and the initial extension
module specific to Google Transit.

The folder structure for the extension currently is python/extensions/.
This extensions folder is an empty python module. Each extension in a
subfolder like googletransit/ must be a valid python module as well.
For more information about the extension structure check the README
in python/extensions/ or the wiki at
http://code.google.com/p/googletransitdatafeed/wiki/FeedValidatorExtensions

This revision contains the googletransit extension. It overrides the
transitfeed.FareAttribute and transitfeed.Schedule classes for adding
new fields and for adding and changing validation code. It creates a
new class FeedInfo for validating the Google Transit specific feed_info.txt.

List of changes of the googletransit extension to the default behavior:
* extensions.googletransit.FareAttribute:
  - extension of transitfeed.FareAttribute
  - adds new field 'agency_id' and function ValidateAgencyId()
* extensions.googletransit.FeedInfo:
  - new class for validating feedinfo.txt
  - validates fields 'feed_publisher_name', 'feed_publisher_url', 'feed_lang',
    'feed_timezone', 'feed_valid_from' and 'feed_valid_until'
  - recognizes field 'feed_version'
  - The valid dates range specified by 'feed_valid_from' and 'feed_valid_until'
    is only used to check the feed validity. It's not used for other purposes.
    In particular, services and service exceptions are not dropped or reduced if
    they are defined outside this valid dates range.
* extensions.googletransit.Schedule:
  - extension of transitfeed.Schedule
  - new feed_info variable and AddFeedInfoObject() method in order to be able to
    register a extensions.googletransit.FeedInfo object in the Schedule
  - validates FeedInfo.feed_lang against Agency.agency_lang
  - validates FeedInfo.feed_timezone against Agency.agency_timezone
  - checks that all Agencies have the same timezone
  - overrides ValidateFeedStartAndExpirationDates() in order to take
    FeedInfo.feed_valid_from and FeedInfo.feed_valid_until into account

Starting the FeedValidator with this extension is done with the command
./feedvalidator.py <feed_filename> --extension extensions.googletransit

Going to localhost:3000 will re-direct you to sign up page.

Before signup page is displayed, it will check if username is defined
in local storage.
If username exists, it will re-direct to signed in.
Else, do nothing (since we are on signup page already).

SignUp:
 - Create user with username, password, birthday, job, email.
 - After user is created, it will re-direct user to signed in page.

SignedIn:
 - Display user information.
 - sign out button will clear local storage, and re-direct user back to
sign up page (since there is no user defined)

Fix upload.py to properly use a local logger

until someone tries to run upload.py with any level of verbosity. Then the

upload.py to properly use a module-scope logger so that rietveld.py doesn't
have to perform invasive surgery, and everything just works.

Extract authentication options handling into a separate function.

It is done in preparation for switching to OAuth2 as default (and only)
authentication method. Having all auth options handled by the same code makes it
easier to gradually add OAuth2 support.

As part of this, some options that would no longer work with OAuth2 (and that
are not being used from anywhere now, as far as I can tell) are removed:
  * Passing account password for authentication via command line.
  * Overriding 'Host' header when making requests to Rietveld (won't work with
    SSL anyway).
  * --account_type option (seems to be ClientLogin specific).

All scripts that use rietveld.Rietveld internally should be able to use cached
credentials created by 'depot-tools-auth' subcommand. Also 'depot-tools-auth'
is the only way to run login flow. If some scripts stumbles over expired or
revoked token, it dies with the error, asking user to run
'depot-tools-auth login <hostname>'.

Password login is still default. OAuth2 can be enabled by passing --oauth2 to
all scripts.

api: add script to generate {geany,geany-scintilla}-gtkdoc.h

The script reads the doxygen xml output and generates two headers (optionally
a single header) that contains all of the plugin API in gtk-doc format.

Two headers because it's preferrable to group Scintilla related stuff
into its own namespace. This is a lot easier if g-ir-scanner can
work with a separate header file. If we change minds later on the script is
prepared to generate only one header.

Move globals into main() function

This prevents running a bunch of top-level code if the module is
ever imported and cleans-up the global namespace.

Use 4-space indentation to follow PEP-8

The other Python scripts already follow this convention.
Rename global "constant" to follow PEP-8 naming
Replace comments and asserts with doc-comments and doc-tests

Fix GtkDoc header generation script to handle references inside typedef

Fix forward reference to enumeration types in GtkDoc header

It's invalid to forward-declare enumerations, yet they might be
referenced by typedefs.

Fix this by outputting enumerations first so typedefs can references
them.  As enumerations can't reference other types, it's safe to place
them before anything else.

gtkdoc: fix gtkdoc header script for structs with inline types

Doxygen adds unhandled xml output for structs that define types inline, for
example struct Foo { enum { FOO, BAR } baz; }. A type definitions precedes the
members. The script wrongly assumed the first sectiondef child of compounddef
would contain all members, but actually this is the case for sectiondefs with
kind=public-attrib (the sectiondef defining the type has kind=public-type).

Fix for browsers with no classList on svg

Some browsers have both svg and classList support but no classList support on svg tags.

To support those cases one would have to use `setAttribute` and `getAttribute`, which (conferring no benefit to the usual case with a more modern browser) might better be done in a custom binding e.g. `svgCss`.
